1755 // Decision made to begin Expulsion // British lieutenant governor Charles Lawrence and the Nova // Scotia Council decided on July 28, 1755, to deport the Acadians. // Although Grand Pr� to this day is the most well-known symbol // of the expulsion, it actually began at Fort Beausejour on August 11. // Acadians were forcibly removed from their colony. The // British military expelled more than half of the roughly fifteen // thousand Acadians who resided in Nova Scotia. Up to ten // thousand Acadians died during the Expulsion from disease, // starvation, neglect, and exposure to the elements, as well as // from violence by the British. // Atchafalaya // National Heritage Area

1764 // Acadians settle in Louisiana // From 1764 to 1789 about 3,000 exiled Acadians traveled by // ship to live in Louisiana, some taking as long as six months // and arriving in the same clothes they were deported in, // Louisiana was then a colony of Spain, but the Acadians managed // to retain their French culture. Their descendants, the Cajuns, // continued to keep their langage and lifestyles. This culture is // alive and well today and well over 500,000 descendants can // be found in the parishes of Louisiana which make up // Acadiana. // E.L. 1847 // Henry Wadsworth Longfellow publishes poem, Evangeline // The famous American poet Henry Wadsworth Longfellow // published Evangeline in 1847. It would eventually be translated // into over 130 languages. The world discovered the tragic history // of the Acadian people, as Evangeline and her love, Gabriel // gecame folk heroes. // Although there were many regional differences, Acadians were // able to maintain a distinct culture. // The Evangeline Oak became the most photographed tree in the // United States and thousands upon thousands of tourists flooded // the town of St. Martinville, nicknamed "Le Petit Paris". // The story of this culture, history and romance of the tourist // mecca would be told in a film titled, Evangeline, in 1929, starring // Delores del Rio, who would go on to donate the statue of // Evangeline that sits in the rear of the exterior of // St. Martin de Tours Catholic Church, which is actually one // of the first Catholic Churches in North America. // St. Martin de Tours // Catholic Church // Mother Church of // the Acadians // Atchafalaya // NATIONAL HERITAGE AREA
